<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.abo.fi/~mlindroo/SpaceLVs/Slides/index.htm">www.abo.fi/~mlindroo/SpaceLVs/Slides/index.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
 Looking through these big booster concepts, it's a wonder that nobody tried tripropellant engines. It'd be interesting to see if something like ROMBUS could be made entire single-stage this way, since much of the propellant has less bulk than LH2.<br>
<br>
<br>
 Salkeld also worked on lots of HTHL designs during the period:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Most designs were based on the &quot;tripropellant propulsion&quot; concept. Hydrocarbon fuels such as kerosene or JP-5 have a higher density than liquid hydrogen fuel. This reduces the size and weight of the propellant tanks, but hydrogen produces a much higher exhaust velocity which means less fuel is required. Salkeld suggested it would make sense to use both hydrocarbon and hydrogen fuel. The high bulk density of hydrocarbon fuel is quite important during launch, when high thrust matters more than exhaust velocity. Later on, the vehicle -- now considerably lighter -- switches to highly efficient oxygen/hydrogen as it leaves the atmosphere.<br>
<br>
...<br>
<br>
 Boeing claimed HTHL SSTO would be practical e.g. if tripropellant (LH2,LOX, hydrocarbon) engines were used)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
 There was a rash of work on big water landing BDBs during the same time.<br>
Here's a monster, from a time before O'Neill worked on extraterrestrial resources. They'd work very well to launch seed factories (and Orion upper stages), too.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The initial NASA/Johnson Space Center launch studies from 1976 assumed a very large reusable VTVL TSTO vehicle (right) would be used for launching 700-tonne SPS subassemblies into a 500km low Earth orbit. The expected recurring launch cost was approximately $23 million [1976] or $33 per kilogram. All launch vehicle components except the large payload fairing would be reusable and the 1st &amp; 2nd stages would land at sea.<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.abo.fi/~mlindroo/OutSpace/2hlvjsc1.gif">Click here for image</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
