<br>
Does anyone have any data on the following things:<br>
<br>
1) isp of the first stage Sea Dragon.  I am gonna use 250 if nobody has anything.<br>
<br>
2) Fuel feed rates as a function of time.  I found data on the feed and chamber pressures, and am willing to bet that the feed rates decline roughly in proportion to those figures, but some confirmation would be nice.  <br>
<br>
According to some rough chicken scratches I have made so far, the Sea Dragon first stage HAD to be throttled down, or else it would have been slamming along at a whopping 5.5 g's right before first stage burnout.  Talk about a rough ride!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
<br>
John Fraz: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   it's a wonder that nobody tried tripropellant engines.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Heh, you just love those funky solutions to the problems with chemical props, don't you?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
In my opinion, if we HAD to make use of chemical fuels to run a BDB and still wanted better performance, we'd simply use better fuels.  For example:<br>
<br>
Oxygen Diflouride and Diborane.  OF2 is more energetic than LOX, and is more dense than LOX at equivalent temps.  It has a slightly higher molecular weight than LOX, but the extra energy compensates for that.<br>
<br>
Diborane (B2H6) is nice and light in atomic weight, and has the super energetic boron to combine with the flourine in the oxidiser.  The real win is that diborane is over 6 times as dense in liquid form as LH2!  It is cryogenic, but its boiling point is way up there compared to LH2.(About 180 kelvin)<br>
<br>
Oxygen Diflouride and Diborane have a vacuum Isp of about 445 versus 470 or so for Lox/LH2.  For a BDB or even a chemical SSTO they are about the perfect set of propellants.  Did I mention that it's hypergolic if you treat it right? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
If the X-33 had been designed to use OF2/Diborane, it'd be flying now.  &quot;Slush&quot; hydrogen is a total joke.<br>
<br>
Of course, the down side is that both OF2 and Diborane are deadly poisonous and powerful corrosives.  Fuel spills are a PROBLEM.  The exhaust is nothing to go breathing, either.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Plus, the reaction temps are pretty high with these two, since moving the heavier mole weight exhaust is compensated by more energy in the chemistry.  Engines would be a chore to keep happy.<br>
<br>
But that's just engineering, right?  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Slightly less radical than OF2 and Diborane is OF2 and RP1.  <br>
<br>
OF2 and jet fuel has Isp of about 350, vs 265 or so for LOX and RP1.   Plus it's denser, so less weight on the tankage.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
EDIT: Oh, duh, I should let ya know how dense this stuff is: <br>
<br>
OF2 is 1.55 kg/liter or more if you super cool it to LOX temps<br>
Diborane is 437 grams per liter<br>
LOX is about 1.15 kg/liter at boiling point<br>
LH2 is a mere 71 grams per liter unless you &quot;slush&quot; it, which might get you to a whopping 78 grams/liter.<br>
RP1 is 800 grams per liter<br>
<br>
