<br>
 And tripropellant is too funky for you?<br>
 I'd like to see about CH4-LH2/LOX tripropellant (burn the CH4 in the first stage). Tonnages of kerosene rocket fuels aren't too pretty, so maybe going a little lower performance but cleaner CH4 would still be worth it. Note that the entire fuel load for such a booster could be made at sea.<br>
<br>
 Fuel spills and exhaust isn't that much of a problem with Sea Dragon, obviously. Again, kerosenes would last long enough to reach somebody's waters unless you cleaned it up, but how to do that with a catastrophic booster malf?<br>
 Equatorial deep ocean waters are mostly dead sterile. Nearby Launch crews could be protected from OF2/B2H6, but how does it decompose in sunlight, H20, and air? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/umauk2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 43<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/22/02 10:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=527.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Fuel/propellant selections</span><hr size=1> Discovery 1  <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  May I ask, what properties of OF2 make it more energetic than LOX? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
heh.  It's two-thirds flourine?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   The reason I like OF2 over simple liquid flourine is the fact that mean as it is, OF2 is WAY easier to handle than pure flourine.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Take a look at this periodic table:  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.speclab.com/elements/">www.speclab.com/elements/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Notice that Oxygen and Flourine are right next to each other, with Oxygen being slightly lighter.  Both of them are light elements, so their outer electron shell only accepts 8 electrons maximum.  (The innermost shell holds two, and is thus full.)  Every element on the second row of the periodic table can have a maximum of 10 electrons in the electron shells.  (2 in the inner shell, 8 in the outer.)<br>
<br>
Looking left and right from flourine, the number of electrons in the outer shell is 8 for neon, which is almost totally non-reactive since its outer electron shell is full.  Oxygen is 2 electrons short of the full eight, Nitrogen is three, Carbon is four, etc.  <br>
<br>
Now, the closer that outer shell comes to being full, the more it WANTS to be full.  So, flourine reacts with a great deal of energy, even more than oxygen.<br>
<br>
That's where the extra energy come from, and it is enough to outweigh the extra molar mass of flourine.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
john fraz:  <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  And tripropellant is too funky for you? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Heh.  Yeah, actually it is.  While there are considerable engineering difficulties with OF2/B2H6, they are simply a matter of degree, not a matter of complexity.  Complexity kills, I firmly believe.  <br>
<br>
I would much rather address issues (if we are FORCED to use chemical propellants) of degree as long as it keeps the complexity of the design down.<br>
<br>
Tri-propellant involves extra piping and more importantly valves, and even more importantly pumps.  Can a CH4 pump be used for LH2?  Or do you have to spool down one set of pumps in flight and wind up a different set?  Under varying G forces and vibration loads?<br>
<br>
I'd rather over-engineer a single set of pumps to pump meaner stuff.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   It's a philosophical thing, I guess....<br>
<br>
The difference between Isp 445 and Isp 470 is not THAT much.<br>
<br>
As for the behavior of spills at sea:  Both chemicals are gas at STP, and are reactive enough that they would quickly break down and combine/dilute away in the sea.<br>
<br>
<br>
